<subSubSection id="C30EAB87FFE01744FF5FC6ACFC7C93C3" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BABF80CFFE01744FF5FC6ACFC7C93C3" blockId="2.[166,1225,373,784]" pageId="2" pageNumber="101">
D e s c r i p t i o n. The shell in water samples from light- to dark-brown, in glycerol discolored to transparent. The cell shape is slightly ovoid, almost rounded. Shell length 86–188 µm, width 81–162 µm Shell surface is rough and covered with irregularly-shaped siliceous plate particles and pieces of diatoms. Terminally located aperture is very small (11–25 µm), circular, not surrounded with particles. Morphological and morphometrical characteristics of 
<taxonomicName id="4C14838FFFE01744FEF2C50CFDAC93FD" authority="Snegovaya &amp; Tahirova, 2015" authorityName="Snegovaya &amp; Tahirova" authorityYear="2015" box="[374,528,628,654]" class="Lobosa" family="Difflugiidae" genus="Difflugia" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Arcellinida" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" phylum="Amoebozoa" rank="species" species="alekperovi" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis id="B960241EFFE01744FEF2C50CFDAC93FD" box="[374,528,628,654]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="101">D. alekperovi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2539965FFE01744FD9CC50CFDF393E3" box="[536,591,629,656]" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are shown in 
<figureCitation id="132FE489FFE01744FD7CC50CFCC693E3" box="[760,890,629,656]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[164,197,1738,1760]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,830,1704]" captionTargetId="figure-265@2.[166,1225,830,1704]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 4–7. Difflugia alekperovi sp. n.: 4–5 — LM photographs; 6–7 — SEM photographs. Рис. 4–7. Difflugia alekperovi sp.n.: 4–5 — фотографии,выполненная при помощи световой микроскопии (LM); 6–7 — фотографии, выполненная при помощи электронной микроскопии (SEM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6412759" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6412759/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="101">figures 4–7</figureCitation>
and table 1. Living cells not observed. Very rare species, we found it only in autumn and spring.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30EAB87FFE01745FF5FC5CCFD1E93AE" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="102" pageId="2" pageNumber="101" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BABF80CFFE01745FF5FC5CCFD1E93AE" blockId="2.[166,1225,373,784]" lastBlockId="3.[174,1233,418,797]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="102" pageId="2" pageNumber="101">
